      <section class="bk-section" id="section-intro">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Why Romans?</h2>

        <p>Paul writes to a church he did not plant, preparing them for his visit and seeking their partnership for a mission to Spain. But the letter becomes something far larger than a travel itinerary — it is the most sustained and systematic exposition of the gospel in the New Testament. Paul wants Rome to understand the gospel he preaches before he arrives, so that they can assess, embrace, and fund it.</p>

        <p>The letter addresses a real pastoral crisis: tension between Jewish and Gentile believers in Rome. Paul's response is not to referee between factions but to reground both groups in the same gospel — the righteousness of God received the same way (faith) by every person, regardless of ethnic heritage or law-observance.</p>

        <div class="bk-thesis">
          <span class="bk-thesis__label">Central Thesis</span>
          "For in it [the gospel] the righteousness of God is revealed from faith for faith" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 1:17">1:17</a>). God's righteousness is both his own righteous character and the righteous standing he gives to those who believe.
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-condemnation">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Universal Condemnation (1:18–3:20)</h2>

        <p>Paul's opening argument is forensic and deliberately uncomfortable: all humanity stands condemned before God. He begins with Gentiles (1:18–32), whose suppression of the knowledge of God they have in creation leads to the full unraveling of human life. Then he turns on any reader who thinks themselves morally superior (ch. 2) — including Jewish readers who possess the law but do not keep it. By 3:9–20 the verdict is locked: "None is righteous, no, not one."</p>

        <p>This section is not pessimism for its own sake. Paul is systematically closing every escape route so that the grace of 3:21 arrives as the only door left standing.</p>

        <div class="bk-key-term">
          <span class="bk-key-term__word">Wrath of God</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__original">ὀργὴ θεοῦ (orgē theou)</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__def">Not arbitrary divine rage but God's settled, holy opposition to everything that destroys what he made. In 1:18–32 it is revealed in part now, as God "gives over" humanity to the consequences of its own choices.</span>
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-justification">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Justification by Faith (3:21–5:21)</h2>

        <p>The great "but now" of 3:21 pivots everything. Apart from the law, the righteousness of God has been made known — through faith in Jesus Christ, for all who believe. The death of Christ is both a propitiation (satisfying divine justice) and a demonstration (proving God's righteousness). The result: God is both just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 3:26">3:26</a>).</p>

        <p>Chapters 4–5 anchor this in Scripture (Abraham believed and it was counted as righteousness, before circumcision) and in its effects: peace with God, access to grace, hope of glory, and reconciliation through Christ's death.</p>

        <div class="bk-key-term">
          <span class="bk-key-term__word">Justification</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__original">δικαίωσις (dikaiōsis)</span>
          <span class="bk-key-term__def">A legal declaration that the accused is righteous — not the making-righteous of character (that is sanctification) but the pronouncing-righteous of standing before God's court. The ground is Christ's righteousness imputed; the instrument is faith.</span>
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-sanctification">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Dead to Sin, Alive in Christ (Chs. 6–8)</h2>

        <p>If justification is the verdict, chapters 6–8 are the new life that flows from it. United to Christ in his death and resurrection, believers are "dead to sin and alive to God" (6:11). The old self is crucified; sin no longer has dominion. Chapter 7 explores the painful reality of remaining sin — the tension of wanting what is right but finding another power at work — and chapter 8 resolves it in the Spirit.</p>

        <p>Chapter 8 is one of the peaks of the New Testament: no condemnation (v.1), the Spirit of adoption crying "Abba" (v.15), all creation groaning toward redemption (v.19–22), the Spirit interceding in unutterable groaning (v.26), and the indestructible promise that nothing can separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 8:38-39">vv.38–39</a>).</p>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-israel">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">God's Faithfulness to Israel (Chs. 9–11)</h2>

        <p>If the gospel is for Gentiles equally, what happened to God's promises to Israel? Paul refuses to allow this to be treated as a side question. Chapters 9–11 are a sustained argument that God has not failed his word. Election, hardening, the olive tree — all move toward Paul's conclusion: "a partial hardening has come upon Israel, until the fullness of the Gentiles has come in," and ultimately "all Israel will be saved" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 11:25-26">11:25–26</a>).</p>

        <p>The section closes in a doxology that acknowledges the inscrutability of God's ways while affirming their depth: "For from him and through him and to him are all things. To him be glory forever" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 11:36">11:36</a>).</p>
      </section>


      <section class="bk-section" id="section-ethics">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">The Transformed Life (Chs. 12–15)</h2>

        <p>The pivot from indicative to imperative: "I appeal to you therefore, brothers, by the mercies of God, to present your bodies as a living sacrifice" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 12:1">12:1</a>). The "therefore" links everything in chapters 12–15 to the gospel of chapters 1–11. Transformed living is not the condition of grace; it is its consequence.</p>

        <p>Paul addresses life in the community (ch. 12), submission to civil authority (ch. 13), the strong and weak in faith over food regulations (chs. 14–15), and the call to welcome one another as Christ welcomed you. The letter's practical closing mirrors its doctrinal opening: the same gospel that levels all humanity before God's condemnation now levels all before his welcome.</p>
      </section>


      <!-- ── DISCUSSION QUESTIONS ── -->
      <section class="bk-section" id="section-questions">
        <h2 class="bk-section__heading">Discussion Questions</h2>
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-muted);margin-bottom:1.5rem">For individual reflection or group study.</p>

        <div class="bk-questions">
          <h3 class="bk-questions__title">Book-Level Questions</h3>
          <ol class="bk-questions__list">
            <li class="bk-question">Paul says he is "not ashamed of the gospel" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 1:16">1:16</a>). What would it mean to be ashamed of it? In what contexts do you feel that pull? What does the gospel's power to save have to do with overcoming that shame?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">Romans 1–3 argues that every person has suppressed the truth about God and stands under condemnation. How does this universal diagnosis sit with modern instincts about human goodness? Why is it necessary before the gospel can be received?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">Justification is a legal declaration, not a change of character. Why does that distinction matter? How is knowing you are declared righteous different from just trying harder to be good?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">Chapter 8 promises that nothing can separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus. What does that promise cost Paul to write (consider his hardships in 8:35–36)? How does his confidence coexist with that reality rather than denying it?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">Romans 9–11 is the most theologically dense section on divine election in the New Testament. What is at stake in the question of whether God keeps his promises to Israel? How does your answer to that question affect what you believe about God's promises to you?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">The "strong" and "weak" in chapters 14–15 disagree over food and holy days. Paul tells the strong to limit their freedom for the sake of the weak. What does this say about how theological conviction and communal love are meant to relate?</li>
            <li class="bk-question">Romans grounds ethics in the mercies of God (12:1), not in rules or fear. How does that foundation change the motivation for living rightly? Where do you notice yourself living from the wrong foundation?</li>
          </ol>
        </div>


        <div class="bk-ch-questions">
          <h3 class="bk-ch-questions__title">Chapter Questions</h3>
          <p class="bk-ch-questions__note">One or two focused questions per chapter.</p>
          <div class="bk-ch-grid">

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 1</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 1:1-32">Rom 1</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Paul describes God's wrath being revealed as God "giving over" humanity to its own desires (vv. 24, 26, 28). What does it mean that judgment can look like getting what we want? Where do you see this pattern in the world or in yourself?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 2</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 2:1-29">Rom 2</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"You who preach against stealing, do you steal?" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 2:21">v. 21</a>). Paul's argument is that possessing the law does not mean keeping it. Where in your own life is there a gap between what you teach or believe and how you live?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 3</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 3:1-31">Rom 3</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"God is both just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 3:26">v. 26</a>). Why is it important that he is <em>both</em>, not just one or the other? What would be lost if he forgave sin without dealing with it?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 4</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 4:1-25">Rom 4</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Abraham was justified before circumcision — before any religious rite or law-keeping (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 4:10-11">vv. 10–11</a>). Why does the timing matter to Paul's argument? What does it imply about the relationship between faith and religious practice?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 5</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 5:1-21">Rom 5</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"We rejoice in our sufferings, knowing that suffering produces endurance" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 5:3">v. 3</a>). What makes this different from just putting a brave face on difficulty? How does hope grounded in God's love (v. 5) change the texture of suffering?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 6</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 6:1-23">Rom 6</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"How can we who died to sin still live in it?" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 6:2">v. 2</a>). Paul's answer is that union with Christ in death means union in resurrection — the old self is gone. What does it look like to "reckon" yourself dead to sin (v. 11) rather than just trying harder not to sin?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 7</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 7:1-25">Rom 7</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"I do not do what I want, but I do the very thing I hate" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 7:15">v. 15</a>). Is Paul describing a pre-conversion experience, a normal Christian experience, or something else? What comfort (if any) do you find in this passage?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 8</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 8:1-39">Rom 8</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Nothing will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 8:39">v. 39</a>). Paul lists tribulation, distress, persecution, famine, nakedness, danger, sword. Which item on that list feels most threatening to you? How does this promise address it?</p>
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">The Spirit intercedes for us "with groanings too deep for words" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 8:26">v. 26</a>). What does it mean that prayer can function even when we don't know how or what to pray?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 9</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 9:1-33">Rom 9</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Paul says he could wish himself accursed for the sake of his kinsmen according to the flesh (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 9:3">v. 3</a>). What kind of love is this? Is there anyone for whom you have felt this kind of longing?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 10</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 10:1-21">Rom 10</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"How are they to believe in him of whom they have never heard? And how are they to hear without someone preaching?" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 10:14">v. 14</a>). What does Paul's logic in this passage say about the urgency of mission? Does it change how you think about your own responsibility?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 11</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 11:1-36">Rom 11</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Oh, the depth of the riches and wisdom and knowledge of God! How unsearchable are his judgments and how inscrutable his ways!" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 11:33">v. 33</a>). Paul's doxology follows chapters of hard argument. What does it mean to respond to theology with worship rather than just with conclusions?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 12</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 12:1-21">Rom 12</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Do not be conformed to this world, but be transformed by the renewal of your mind" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 12:2">v. 2</a>). What shapes minds? What specific practices of mind-renewal does Paul seem to have in view in the rest of the chapter?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 13</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 13:1-14">Rom 13</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">Paul commands submission to governing authorities, written under Nero's Rome (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 13:1-4">vv. 1–4</a>). What are the limits of this command? How does this passage sit alongside Revelation's portrayal of Rome as Babylon?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 14</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 14:1-23">Rom 14</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Each of us will give an account of himself to God" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 14:12">v. 12</a>). In a passage about not judging others, Paul still grounds responsibility in individual accountability. How do these two truths — don't judge, but you are accountable — coexist?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 15</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 15:1-33">Rom 15</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">"Welcome one another as Christ has welcomed you, for the glory of God" (<a class="ref" data-ref="Romans 15:7">v. 7</a>). Paul addresses ethnic and cultural tension in the church. What would it cost your community to welcome those whose practices or backgrounds feel foreign? What would motivate it?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bk-ch-card">
              <div class="bk-ch-card__head">
                <span class="bk-ch-card__num">Chapter 16</span>
                <a class="bk-ch-card__ref ref" data-ref="Romans 16:1-27">Rom 16</a>
              </div>
              <div class="bk-ch-card__body">
                <p class="bk-ch-card__q">The closing chapter names 29 individuals, many of them women with significant roles (Phoebe as deacon and patron, Priscilla as co-worker, Junia as apostle). What does the texture of Paul's actual ministry — as revealed in these greetings — tell you about how he thought about the church?</p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div><!-- /.bk-ch-grid -->
        </div><!-- /.bk-ch-questions -->

      </section><!-- /section-questions -->


    </div><!-- /.container -->
  </main>
